1 The Big Idea

2016 is a great year to be a Pok√©mon fan. Pok√©mon Sun and Moon are expected to be release during the holiday season and Niantic‚Äôs Pok√©mon Go due some time later this year. The time has come for us to answer one of the most important questions in life, the one that has brought about most heated discussions for elementary schoolers and grown-ups alike: What is the strongest Pok√©mon of all time?

We set out to answer this question by simulating battles for all Pok√©mon from Generation I to VI, then calculate their variance-adjusted average win rate, in the tradition of the Sharpe ratio often employed in portfolio analysis. The data is obtained from the Pok√©mon Database including type advatages, Pok√©dex and moves database. All 800 Pok√©mons underwent 100 with one another resulting in 800 x 800 x 100 battles simulated in total. We then computed the average variance-adjusted win rates and rank all Pok√©mons accordingly.

2 Data Processing

We scraped dual-type advantage tables, Pok√©mon statistics, and power and accuracy of all moves from Pok√©mon Database. Then process them for our battle simulation function.

2.4 Process Types for Each Pok√©mon

We process primary and secondary types of each Pok√©mon for the battle simulation function.

pokemon$Type1 <- rep(NA,dim(pokemon)[1])
pokemon$Type2 <- rep(NA,dim(pokemon)[1])

for (i in types){
    for (j in 1:dim(pokemon)[1]){
        if(grepl(i,pokemon[j,'Type'])){
            if (is.na(pokemon[j,'Type1'])){
                 pokemon[j,'Type1']<-i
            }
            else {
                pokemon[j,'Type2']<-i
            }
        }
    }
}

3.3 Average Accuracy and Power of Moves

We also calculate the average base power and accuracy of all moves. This resulted in average base power 75.06 and 95.24% base accuracy. We will use this in our battle simulation function in the next section.

url <- "http://pokemondb.net/move/all"
moves <- url %>%
  read_html() %>%
  html_nodes(xpath='//*[@id="moves"]') %>%
  html_table() %>%
  as.data.frame()

#Convert power and accuracy to numeric
moves$Power<-sapply(moves$Power,as.numeric)
moves$Acc.<-sapply(moves$Acc.,as.numeric)
#Get their averages
m_power<-mean(moves$Power,na.rm = TRUE)
m_acc<-mean(moves$Acc.,na.rm = TRUE)
m_power
## [1] 75.05833
m_acc
## [1] 95.23702

4 Battle Simulation

4.1 Battle Simulation Function

The simulation is based on Generation IV rules with all Pok√©mons assumed to have full IVs and EVs at level 100. Both of them take turn, not unlike in the game, attacking each other with STAB, physical or special moves of their primary or secondary type on each other, depending on which does more damage, and the first Pok√©mon to reach 0 HP is said to have lost the round. The moves is assumed to have average power and accuracy (75.06 and 95.24% respectively), assuming Stage 1 critical rate. No nature or ability is taken into account. Since we only allow moves that share a type with the Pok√©mon, when two Pok√©mon that cannot damage each other type-wise such as Rattata (Normal) and Misdreavus (Ghost), we assume a draw.

#Battle simulation function
#Generation VI rules
#Pokemon LV 100 
#Using STAB move with m_power and m_acc with the best type advantage
#Stage 1 critical (6.25%)
#No nature or ability is taken into account
#All IVs = 31, All EVs = 252
#Fights for 100 times each pair

#Damage without type advantage, critical, random and accuracy
damage<-function(atk,def,power=m_power,level=100){
    #STAB * Critical * rand[0.85,1]
    STAB <- 1.5
    (((2*level+10)/250)*(atk/def)*power+2)*1.5
}

#Damage modifier, aka critical, random and accuracy
mod <- function(acc=m_acc){
    crit <-ifelse(runif(1)<=0.0625,1.5,1)
    hit <- ifelse(runif(1)<=acc,1,0)
    mod <- 1.5*crit*hit*runif(1,min=0.85,max=1)
    return(mod)
}

stat_fol <- function(base,iv=31,ev=252,level=100){
    ((2*base+iv+ev/4)*level/100)+5
}

battle<-function(poke1,poke2,times=100,level=100,verbose=FALSE){
    #poke1 stats
    hp1 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke1,'HP'])+5+level
    atk1 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke1,'Attack'])
    def1 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke1,'Defense'])
    spatk1 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke1,'Sp..Atk'])
    spdef1 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke1,'Sp..Def'])
    spd1 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke1,'Speed'])
    type1<-pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke1,'Type']
    type1_1<-pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke1,'Type1']
    type2_1<-pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke1,'Type2']
    
    #poke2 stats
    hp2 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke2,'HP'])+5+level
    atk2 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke2,'Attack'])
    def2 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke2,'Defense'])
    spatk2 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke2,'Sp..Atk'])
    spdef2 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke2,'Sp..Def'])
    spd2 <- stat_fol(pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke2,'Speed'])
    type2<-pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke2,'Type']
    type1_2<-pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke2,'Type1']
    type2_2<-pokemon[pokemon$Name==poke2,'Type2']
    
    #Choose most deadly poke1 move
    type_mod1_1 <-d_type_adv[type2,type1_1]
    type_mod2_1 <- d_type_adv[type2,type2_1]
    
    atk_type1_1<-type_mod1_1*damage(atk1,def2)
    spatk_type1_1<-type_mod1_1*damage(spatk1,spdef2)
    atk_type2_1<-type_mod2_1*damage(atk1,def2)
    spatk_type2_1<-type_mod2_1*damage(spatk1,spdef2)
    
    final_atk1 <- max(atk_type1_1,spatk_type1_1,
                      atk_type2_1,spatk_type2_1,na.rm = TRUE)
    
    #Choose most deadly poke2 move
    type_mod1_2 <-d_type_adv[type1,type1_2]
    type_mod2_2 <- d_type_adv[type1,type2_2]
    
    atk_type1_2<-type_mod1_2*damage(atk2,def1)
    spatk_type1_2<-type_mod1_2*damage(spatk2,spdef1)
    atk_type2_2<-type_mod2_2*damage(atk2,def1)
    spatk_type2_2<-type_mod2_2*damage(spatk2,spdef1)
    
    final_atk2 <- max(atk_type1_2,spatk_type1_2,
                      atk_type2_2,spatk_type2_2,na.rm = TRUE)
    
    #If they can't damage each other, return a draw
    if (final_atk1==0 &final_atk2==0) return(0.5)
    
    #Battle till faint
    win1<-0
    win2<-0
    for (i in 1:times){
        temp1 <-hp1
        temp2 <-hp2
        count <-0
        while (TRUE){
            #if poke2 has more speed add it moves first
            if (spd2>spd1){
                #poke2 hits
                temp1=temp1-final_atk2*mod()
                if (verbose) print(paste(poke2,'attacked for',final_atk2*mod(),sep=' '))
                if (temp1<=0) {
                    win2=win2+1
                    if (verbose) print(paste(poke2,'wins at HP',temp2,sep=' '))
                    break
                }
                #poke1 hits
                temp2=temp2-final_atk1*mod()
                if (verbose) print(paste(poke1,'attacked for',final_atk1*mod(),sep=' '))
                if (temp2<=0) {
                    win1=win1+1
                    if (verbose) print(paste(poke1,'wins at HP',temp1,sep=' '))
                    break
                }
            }
            #if poke2 has more speed add it moves first
            else if(spd1>spd2){
                #poke1 hits
                temp2=temp2-final_atk1*mod()
                if (verbose) print(paste(poke1,'attacked for',final_atk1*mod(),sep=' '))
                if (temp2<=0) {
                    win1=win1+1
                    if (verbose) print(paste(poke1,'wins at HP',temp1,sep=' '))
                    break
                }
                #poke2 hits
                temp1=temp1-final_atk2*mod()
                if (verbose) print(paste(poke2,'attacked for',final_atk2*mod(),sep=' '))
                if (temp1<=0) {
                    win2=win2+1
                    if (verbose) print(paste(poke2,'wins at HP',temp2,sep=' '))
                    break
                }
            }
            #Otherwise use a tiebreaker
            else{
                #If true, poke1 hits first
                if (sample(c(TRUE,FALSE))[1]){
                    #poke1 hits
                    temp2=temp2-final_atk1*mod()
                    if (verbose) print(paste(poke1,'attacked for',final_atk1*mod(),sep=' '))
                    if (temp2<=0) {
                        win1=win1+1
                        if (verbose) print(paste(poke1,'wins at HP',temp1,sep=' '))
                        break
                    }
                    #poke2 hits
                    temp1=temp1-final_atk2*mod()
                    if (verbose) print(paste(poke2,'attacked for',final_atk2*mod(),sep=' '))
                    if (temp1<=0) {
                        win2=win2+1
                        if (verbose) print(paste(poke2,'wins at HP',temp2,sep=' '))
                        break
                    } 
                }
                #If false, poke2 hits first
                else{
                    #poke2 hits
                    temp1=temp1-final_atk2*mod()
                    if (verbose) print(paste(poke2,'attacked for',final_atk2*mod(),sep=' '))
                    if (temp1<=0) {
                        win2=win2+1
                        if (verbose) print(paste(poke2,'wins at HP',temp2,sep=' '))
                        break
                    }
                    #poke1 hits
                    temp2=temp2-final_atk1*mod()
                    if (verbose) print(paste(poke1,'attacked for',final_atk1*mod(),sep=' '))
                    if (temp2<=0) {
                        win1=win1+1
                        if (verbose) print(paste(poke1,'wins at HP',temp1,sep=' '))
                        break
                    }
                }
            }
        }
    }
    return(win1/times)
}

4.2 Simulate Battles for All Pairs of Pok√©mons

We simulate 100 battles for each pair of Pok√©mons, resulting in 800 x 800 x 100 total battles simulated. Then we record the win rate for each pair. For instance, if we pitch Bulbasaur against Caterpie and the function returns 0.99, it means that Bulbasaur has a 99% win rate against Caterpie as a result of the 100 battles. When the same Pok√©mon is matched, such as Pikachu vs Pikachu, we assume a draw. The result of all battles is saved to result.rds for future reference.

if (!file.exists('result.rds')){
   result <- data.frame(matrix(1:800/100,nrow=dim(pokemon)[1],ncol=dim(pokemon)[1]))
    rownames(result)<-pokemon$Name
    colnames(result)<-pokemon$Name
    count<-0
    for (i in pokemon$Name){
        for (j in pokemon$Name){
            #Same pokemon assumes draw
            if (i==j){
                result[i,j]<-0.5
            } else{
            result[i,j]<-battle(i,j)
            }
            count=count+1
            print(paste(count,i,j,sep=' '))
        }
    }

    #Save to RDS
    saveRDS(result,'result.rds') 
} else {
    result<-readRDS('result.rds')
}

4.3 Best Variance-Adjusted Average Win Rate

At the core of every strongest-Pok√©mon argument is how you define strongest: the toughest wall, the most destructive sweeper, the most advantageous type, and the list go on. Here we define strongest as the best variance-adjusted average win rate. The rationale is two-fold. First, it should be straight forward that after 100 battles with each Pok√©mon, a Pok√©mon with a high average win rate would be strong. However, we need to take into account the variability of its win rate. For instance, compare a Pok√©mon that wins all of its battles 50% of times with a Pok√©mon that wins half of its battles 100% of times but loses the rest 100% of times. Their average win rate is both 50% but we would rather have a more consistent Pok√©mon that is the former. Below is the average win rate vs standard deviation of win rate plot of all Pok√©mons by primary types.

#Row SD function
rowSDs <- function(x) {
  sqrt(rowSums((x - rowMeans(x))^2)/(dim(x)[2] - 1))
}

#Plot average win rate vs standard deviation
rank_poke<-cbind(pokemon,winrate=rowMeans(result),sd=rowSDs(result))
g<-ggplot(data=rank_poke,aes(x=winrate,y=sd))
g+geom_point(aes(color=Type1))+xlab('Average Win Rates')+
    ylab('Standard Deviation of Win Rates')+
    ggtitle("Reward vs Risk Plot by Primary Types")

Therefore, we adopted the Sharpe Ratio, a variance-adjusted return metric for an asset in capital asset pricing model. We use the average win rate of all battles (yes, all 64 million of them) as the benchmark win rate. We calculate our variance-adjusted average win rate by subtracting the average win rate of each Pok√©mon by excess win rate per standard deviation of it.

This way, if a stranger challenges you to a 1-on-1 Pok√©mon battle and you don‚Äôt know what he has, you know that your best and most consistent chance of winning is to choose Palkia.

#Benchmark return
b_return <- mean(rowMeans(result))

#Sharpe ratio
sharpe <- (rowMeans(result)-b_return)/rowSDs(result)

#Ranking according to variance-adjusted price
sharped <- data.frame(sort(sharpe,decreasing=TRUE))
kable(head(sharped,20),col.names='Shrape Ratio')
